ce:section.ce:para:
The intention of this work is to procure a stimuli-sensitive and targeted drug delivery system with high and genial drug loading efficiency based on polymers. Polymeric networks behave as bioactive drug carriers that can conjugate drugs among their cavities in addition to their surface. This conjugation elevates drug loading capacity and raises the drug plasma’s half-life, so patients can take less dose of the desired drug daily. The STB loading efficiency computing was appraised by mixing one milliliter of PD@His.GQD carrier with 0.5 mL of different STB concentrations in the range 5.000−3000 μg mL−1 in 2 mL of PB buffer of pH = 7.2 in the shaking incubator at Temp = 25 °C. Then by gauging unbound STB via standard calibration curve and collecting the STB loaded PD@His.GQD by dialysis for 24 h, the percentage of STB loading efficiency (Ea%) was calculated via monitoring the FI changes at λex = 380 nm (Fig. 9
                           ). As seen in the Fig. 9, the percentage of STB loading efficiency raises with increasing the STB concentration and reaches to 99 % at STB concentration of 3000 μg mL−1. As a matter of fact, the PD@His.GQD vast surface area, a lot of polymeric networks, and existence the His.GQD functional groups on the polymeric networks carrier lead to extraordinary ability of the synthesized PD@His.GQD carrier to load numerous amounts of STB and high drug loading efficiency. Different drug delivery systems have been proposed to reduce the side effects of sunitinib on healthy cells. Table 1
                            lists some of these drug delivery systems and the sunitinib loading efficiency percentage in them has been compared with the synthesized PD@His.GQD in this project [29–35]. As shown in the Table 1, the synthesized PD@His.GQD has higher loading efficiency percentage than other drug carriers in accordance with the reasons mentioned above.

Due to their very high resistance to body fluids, these carriers can easily move in the body until they reach to the diseased tissue without destroying and releasing the loaded drug. This leads to significantly lessen drug side effects on healthy tissue via drug dose controlling, and so obtaining a favorable drug release kinetic [26]. Due to the physical and chemical properties of these polymeric drug carriers, the process of drug release from them is based on three mechanisms include: diffusion, swelling or erosion [26,27]. The important note is that the polymeric carrier hydrolysis causes their destruction and excretion from the body after releasing their loaded drug. In this work a PD@His.GQD carrier has been synthesized, so to predict the STB release mechanism, the obtained in vitro release data were reviewed via four mathematical models: Zero-order that describes the system where the drug release rate is independent of its concentration and the process of constant drug release from the carrier, First-order that the release rate is directly proportional to the drug concentration undergoing reaction (greater the concentration faster the reaction), Higuchi that the release according to this model occurs in the homogeneous/solid matrix carrier through drug solubility given that the initial drug concentration is greater than its dissolution rate and Korsmeyer-Peppas model that depicts drug release via diffusion mechanism from polymeric carriers (Table 2
                        ) [14,25,26]. In all equations in the Table 2, “F” denotes to the fraction of released drug concentration at time “t” to initial drug concentration. According to Korsmeyer-Peppas model and as shown in its formula, the ratio of released drug at time “t” to the total initial loaded drug is related to the “n” factor of drug release time that “n” value determines the type of drug release mechanism (Table 3
                        ) [26]. Evaluation of the obtained results from the fitting in vitro STB release data at pH = 5.4 and Temp = 37 ͦ C and comparison of Regression coefficients (R2) and rate constant factors (k) of all four models shows that the data have the highest correlation with the Korsmeyer-Peppas model (Table 4
                        ). As it mentioned in Table 3, the Korsmeyer-Peppas kinetic model describes the drug release mechanism from polymeric carriers, so according to Table 4, the obtained in vitro STB release data was fitted with this model that expresses the STB release mechanism from PD@His.GQD carrier is controlled by diffusion. It means that, the synthesized diffusion-controlled PD@His.GQD carrier consists of a repository (STB core) in a polymeric matrix where the diffusion and STB dissolving occurs in that due to the concentration gradient, then it leaves the carrier and enters to the kidney cancerous cells [28].
